tes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow humans adapt to life in an area prone to natural disasters is an intriguing study for the social sciences. In this volume, experts from several disciplines explore the adaptation process of prehistoric societies in the volcanic Arenal region of Costa Rica from about 2000 BC to the Spanish Conquest at about AD 1500. The data in this volume come from a survey of the region conducted with the latest remote sensing technology. Sheets and his coauthors have compiled a detailed record of human settlements in the area, including dozens of archaeological sites and a network of prehistoric footpaths that reveals patterns of travel and communication across the region. The Arenal peoples prospered in their precarious environment apparently by taking advantage of food and lithic resources, keeping population levels low, and avoiding environmental degradation. These findings will interest a wide interdisciplinary audience in anthropology and archaeology, earth sciences, technology, geography, and human ecology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aVolcanism - Costa Rica. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aBlanco Vargas, Aida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, John E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChenault, Mark L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClary, Karen H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoopes, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahaney, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Meredith H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r